sql:
SELECT COUNT(*) 
FROM income_ranges 
WHERE lower_bound < 30000 AND upper_bound > 25000;

SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM locations
WHERE median_income > (SELECT AVG(upper_bound) FROM income_ranges);

SELECT AVG(poverty_rate) AS average_poverty_rate
FROM locations
WHERE median_income BETWEEN 40000 AND 49999;

external_knowledge:
- "median income" is the middle value of incomes in a location when they are listed in ascending order;
- "poverty rate" is the percentage of the population living below the poverty line;
- "income range" is a category that groups incomes into specific brackets.

- 'Most affluent location' refers to the location with the highest average median income per household;
- 'Population density over a thousand' means the population density is greater than 1000 people per square mile;
- 'Household has at least two members' means the household size is 2 or more;
- 'Median income within the range of $20,000 to $24,999 per person' means the median income is at least the lower bound of this range, adjusted by the number of people in the household.

- "blossoming" refers to areas that are thriving or growing well;
- "affluent regions" refers to areas with a median income above $40,000;
- "income brackets" refers to the income ranges defined in the `income_ranges` table.

- "Median income" refers to the middle value of a distribution of incomes;
- "Household size" is the number of people living in a household;
- "Income ranges" are predefined intervals of income values.

- 'Highest median income range' refers to the income range with the highest median income for each location;
- 'Population exceeding 100,000' filters the locations to those with a population greater than 100,000;
- 'Household size' is the number of people in a household.

